It was, indeed, our friend the financier. I was shocked by the change which had come over him, for
his face which was naturally of a broad and massive mould, was now pinched and fallen in, while his
hair seemed to me at least a shade whiter. He entered with a weariness and lethargy which was even
more painful than his violence of the morning before, and he dropped heavily into the armchair which
I pushed forward for him.

"I do not know what I have done to be so severely tried," said he. "Only two days ago I was a happy
and prosperous man, without a care in the world. Now I am left to a lonely and dishonoured age. One
sorrow comes close upon the heels of another. My niece, Mary, has deserted me."

"Deserted you?"